ğŸŸ© Problem
Customer reviews often contain repeated adjacent characters like â€œlooooveâ€ or â€œamazzzinggâ€.  
You need to clean the review by removing adjacent duplicates until no such pairs remain.

Example:  
"azxxzy" â†’ remove "xx" â†’ azzy â†’ remove "zz" â†’ ay  
"aaccdd" â†’ becomes empty


ğŸŸ© Sample Input
azxxzy

ğŸŸ© Sample Output
ay

ğŸŸ© Solution (Manual Stack)

import java.io.*;
import java.util.*;

public class Solution {

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);
        String s = sc.nextLine();

        char[] arr = new char[s.length()];
        int top = -1;

        for (int i = 0; i < s.length(); i++) {

            char ch = s.charAt(i);

            if (top >= 0 && arr[top] == ch) {
                top--;          // remove duplicate
            } else {
                arr[++top] = ch; 
            }
        }

        if (top == -1) {
            System.out.print("Empty String");
        } else {
            for (int i = 0; i <= top; i++) {
                System.out.print(arr[i]);
            }
        }
    }
}

ğŸŸ© Time Complexity - O(n) â€” each character pushed or removed once
ğŸŸ© Space Complexity - O(n) â€” stack stored in an array
